fr.pyvain.websight.websight.Geometry

Class Segment

  • java.lang.Object
    • fr.pyvain.websight.websight.Geometry.Segment
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Comparable<Segment>

    public class Segment
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<Segment>

    A class that represents a 2-dimensional segment.

    The behaviour of certain computational geometry methods is not guaranteed if segments involved do not lie in [-1000, 1000] x [-1000, 1000]

    Also, note that this class has a natural ordering that is inconsistent with equals. Two segments are equals if their endpoints have the same coordinate. But the natural ordering only considers their y-coordinate at a certain x-coordinate and their gradient. So, if s1.equals(s2) then s1.compareTo(s2) == s2.compareTo(s1) == 0, but the opposite is not necessarly true.

        public Segment(CPoint p1,

        Creates a new Segment of endpoints p1 and p2. Its lower endpoint will be the lowest of p1 and p2, and its higher endpoint will be the highest of p1 and p2. Endpoints must be different.
        Parameters:
        p1 - First endpoint of the segment
        p2 - Second endpoint of the segment

      • intersectionWith

        public CPoint intersectionWith(Segment that)
        Computes the intersection between two non parallel segments. If this intersection is a point, returns it. If segments are parallel, or they don't intersect, returns null. Undefined behaviour if one of the segments is outside [-1000, 1000] (caused by long overflow)
        Parameters:
        that - Segment whose intersection with the receiving segment must be computed
        Returns:
        The closest CPoint (with integral coordinates) to the intersection between the receiving and specified segments if it exists and the segments are not parallel. Null else.

      • nbIntersectionsWithCircle

                                     float radius)
        Returns the number of intersections between the receiving Segment and a circle of specified center point and radius : 0, 1 or 2. Undefined behaviour if the receiving segment is outside [-1000, 1000] (caused by long overflow)
        Parameters:

        radius - The radius of the circle
        Returns:
        the number of intersection between the segment and the circle
